## maps on the web with a bit of midlife crisis

May 10, 2013   
[html](https://inkdroid.org/2013/05/10/maps-on-the-web-with-a-bit-of-midlife-crisis/tag/html) [rest](https://inkdroid.org/2013/05/10/maps-on-the-web-with-a-bit-of-midlife-crisis/tag/rest) [javascript](https://inkdroid.org/2013/05/10/maps-on-the-web-with-a-bit-of-midlife-crisis/tag/javascript) [wikipedia](https://inkdroid.org/2013/05/10/maps-on-the-web-with-a-bit-of-midlife-crisis/tag/wikipedia) [nodejs](https://inkdroid.org/2013/05/10/maps-on-the-web-with-a-bit-of-midlife-crisis/tag/nodejs) [openstreetmap](https://inkdroid.org/2013/05/10/maps-on-the-web-with-a-bit-of-midlife-crisis/tag/openstreetmap) [maps](https://inkdroid.org/2013/05/10/maps-on-the-web-with-a-bit-of-midlife-crisis/tag/maps) 

---

_TL;DR – I created [a JavaScript library](http://edsu.github.io/wikigeo/) for getting GeoJSON out of Wikipedia’s API in your browser (and Node.js). I also created[a little app](http://inkdroid.org/ici/) that uses it to display Wikipedia articles for things near you that need a photograph/image or editorial help._ 

---

I probably don’t need to tell you how much the state of mapping on the Web has changed in the past few years.[I was there](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6xG4oFny2Pk). I can remember trying to get [MapServer](http://mapserver.org/)set up in the late 1990s, with limited success. I was there squinting at how [Adrian Holovaty](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrian%5FHolovaty) reverse engineered a mapping API out of Google Maps at[chicagocrime.org](http://web.archive.org/web/20060408105215/http://www.chicagocrime.org/map/). I was there when Google released their official API, which I used some, and then they changed their terms of service. I was there in the late 2000s using OpenLayers and TileCache, which were so much more approachable than MapServer was a decade earlier. I’m most definitely not a mapping expert, or even an amateur–but you can’t be a Web developer without occasionally needing to dabble, and pretend you are.

I didn’t realize until very recently how easy the cool kids have made it to put maps on the Web. Who knew that in 2013 there would be an open source JavaScript library that lets you add a map to your page in a few lines, and that it’s in use by Flickr, FourSquare, CraigsList, Wikimedia, the Wall Street Journal, and others? Even more astounding: who knew there would be an openly licensed source of map tiles and data, that was created collaboratively by a project with over a million registered users, and that it would be good enough to be used by Apple? I certainly didn’t even dream about it.

Ok, hold that thought…

So, Wikipedia[recently announced](https://blog.wikimedia.org/2013/03/28/add-an-image-to-this-article-uploads-now-live-on-mobile-wikipedia/) that they were making it easy to use your mobile device to add a photograph to a Wikipedia article that lacked an image.

[![](http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7318/8726826906_2e88f9ab6b_b.jpg)](http://www.flickr.com/photos/inkdroid/8726826906/)

When I read about this I thought it would be interesting to see what Wikipedia articles there are about my current location, and which lacked images, so I could go and take pictures of them. Before I knew it I had[a Web app](http://inkdroid.org/ici/) called ici (French for here) that does just that:

[![](http://inkdroid.org/images/ici.png)](http://inkdroid.org/ici/#lat=38.89591781652618&lon=-77.0342230796814&zoom=16) 

Articles that need images are marked with little red cameras. It was pretty easy to add orange markers for Wikipedia articles that had been flagged as needing edits, or citations. Calling it an app is an overstatement: it is just static HTML, JavaScript and CSS that I serve up. HTML’s[geolocation](http://diveintohtml5.info/geolocation.html)features and [Wikipedia’s API](http://en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php) (which has[GeoData](http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Extension:GeoData)enabled) take care of the rest.

After I created the app I got a tweet from a _real_ geo-hacker, Sean Gillies, who asked:

https://twitter.com/sgillies/status/332185543234441216

Sean is right, it would be really useful to have a GeoJSON output from Wikipedia’s API. But I was on a little bit of a tear, so rather than figuring out how to get GeoJSON into MediaWiki and deployed to all the Wikipedia servers I wondered if I could extract ici’s use of the Wikipedia API into a slightly more generalized JavaScript library, that would make it easy to get GeoJSON out of Wikipedia–at least from JavaScript. That quickly resulted in[wikigeo.js](http://edsu.github.io/wikigeo/) which is now getting used in ici. Getting GeoJSON from Wikipedia using wikigeo.js is done in just one line, and then[adding the GeoJSON to a map in Leaflet](http://leafletjs.com/examples/geojson.html) can also be done in one line:

geojson([-73.94, 40.67], function(data) {
    // add the geojson to a Leaflet map
    L.geoJson(data).addTo(map)
});

