I recently learned from[Ivan Herman](http://ivan-herman.name/2009/12/12/rdfa-usage-spreading…/)’s blog that O’Reilly has begun publishing RDFa in their online catalog of books. So if you go and install the[RDFa Highlight](http://www.w3.org/2001/sw/BestPractices/HTML/rdfa-bookmarklet/) bookmarklet and then visit a page like[this](http://oreilly.com/catalog/9780596516499/) and click on the bookmarklet you’ll see something like:

[ ![](http://inkdroid.org/images/oreilly-rdfa.png) ](http://oreilly.com/catalog/9780596516499/) 

Those red boxes you see are graphical depictions of where metadata can be found interleaved in the HTML. In my screenshot you can maybe barely see an assertion involving the title being displayed:

<urn:x-domain:oreilly.com:product:9780596516499.IP> dc:title "Natural Language Processing with Python"

But there is actually quite a lot of metadata hiding in the page, which can be found by running the page through the[RDFa Distiller](http://www.w3.org/2007/08/pyRdfa) (quickly skim over this if your eyes glaze over when you see Turtle):

